This issue is twofold: determine a strategy for registering mimetypes and, at a higher level, register plugins in general.

Similar to how [HyperTerm](https://hyperterm.org/) expects particular keys on the `exports` object, I'd like to do the same with custom `Transforms` (a la [`transformime-react`](https://github.com/nteract/transformime-react)). We have one custom transform right now and I'm expecting us to support some others right out of the box. Here's what I'm expecting for a common interface:

```js
import React from 'react';

const MIMETYPE = 'application/json+myMimetype';

export class CustomTransform extends React.Component {
  shouldComponentUpdate() {
    return false;
  }

  render() {
    const data = this.props.data.toJS();
    return (
      <CustomThing data={data} />
    );
  }
}

CustomTransform.propTypes = {
  data: React.PropTypes.any,
};

CustomTransform.MIMETYPE = MIMETYPE;

exports.transform = CustomTransform;
```

The three main points:

* A CustomTransform is a `React.Component` that expects a payload in the `data` field of the props (which is Immutable.js).
* The mimetype expected to come through on the Jupyter messaging protocol (and in the notebook format) is a static `MIMETYPE` attribute on the transform.
* `exports` has a key called `transform` with the transformer.

Registering it is then a reduction on the store:

```js
[REGISTER_NEW_MIMETYPE]: (state, action) => {
  const { transform } = action;
  const mimetype = transform.MIMETYPE;

  return state.update('displayOrder', displayOrder => displayOrder.splice(0, 0, mimetype)
       .update('transforms', transforms => transforms.set(mimetype, transform);
}
```

